04:47.746 --> 04:52.708
We don't want anybody from this fort
going into Tynin looking for rednecks.

04:52.918 --> 04:55.002
- May I speak, sir?
- Cobb?

04:55.212 --> 04:58.047
Nivens must know nobody
colored killed the sarge.

04:58.256 --> 05:00.174
Well, this is
precautionary, Cobb.

05:00.384 --> 05:03.594
We can't have the Army
engaged in revenge on civilians.

05:03.804 --> 05:07.431
Sir. Are there any suspects, sir?
None.

05:07.641 --> 05:11.435
Oh, come on, now. Everybody
knows it was the Klan.

05:12.604 --> 05:14.563
Were you
an eyewitness, soldier?

05:14.731 --> 05:16.983
They lynched Jefferson
the week I got here.

05:17.150 --> 05:19.193
Two weeks after that, it was...
Henson.

05:19.403 --> 05:22.196
Unless you saw it,
keep your opinions to yourself.

05:22.406 --> 05:23.990
Yes, sir.

05:26.159 --> 05:27.827
And that applies
to everybody else.

05:27.995 --> 05:29.328
Yes, sir.

05:29.538 --> 05:32.498
Tynin has been placed off-limits
to all enlisted personnel.

05:32.666 --> 05:36.585
Oh, come on, captain.
Any man found in the town

05:36.795 --> 05:39.672
will be immediately subject
to court-martial.

05:40.465 --> 05:43.968
Sergeant Waters' replacement will
be assigned in a couple of weeks.

05:44.177 --> 05:48.806
Until then, Cobb,
you're barracks NCO.

05:49.182 --> 05:50.891
Any questions?

05:52.602 --> 05:54.270
Carry on.

05:57.941 --> 06:01.444
Now, what you think?

06:01.611 --> 06:05.072
Taylor and that goddamn colonel,
they know who killed Waters.

06:05.282 --> 06:07.783
Anybody feel like playing
me in some pitty-pat?

06:07.993 --> 06:10.119
I thought all you could
play was flunky.

06:10.328 --> 06:11.412
Yeah.

06:11.621 --> 06:15.332
Wilkie, whose ass you gonna kiss now
that your number one ass is dead?

06:15.542 --> 06:18.669
You know what you can do for me, Henson.
You too, Peterson.

06:18.879 --> 06:21.881
Take it easy.
I'm the one who lost three stripes.

06:22.090 --> 06:25.551
I'm the only man here with kids.
When the man said jump, I jumped.

06:25.761 --> 06:29.305
Come on, don't put your wife and
kids between you and Waters' ass.

06:29.514 --> 06:32.892
I don't kiss nobody's ass, Henson.
I just wanted my stripes back.

06:33.101 --> 06:35.186
Never been no place,
never had nothing.

06:35.395 --> 06:40.066
You can't understand a man like me.
I was a top sergeant of this platoon.

06:40.275 --> 06:44.570
Yeah? Well, now you ain't nothing.
Nothing, Wilkie.

07:06.718 --> 07:09.011
- Recruits, over here.
- Let me see your passes.

07:09.221 --> 07:11.347
Let's go. Let's go.

07:18.438 --> 07:22.149
Hey, wake up. Wake up, boy.

07:22.359 --> 07:24.068
You said Tynin, didn't you?

07:25.487 --> 07:27.404
Yeah, yeah. Ahem. Yeah.

07:27.989 --> 07:29.698
Come on, boy.

07:30.909 --> 07:32.451
Let's go.

07:33.537 --> 07:35.538
- Hang on.
- Here we go again.

07:35.747 --> 07:37.414
I'm from Mississippi.

07:56.893 --> 07:58.811
Captain Davenport?

08:02.816 --> 08:05.359
Corporal Ellis
at your disposal, sir.

08:05.569 --> 08:08.154
I'm to take you
to Colonel Nivens, sir.

08:08.363 --> 08:12.199
Well, let's get rolling, soldier.
Yes, sir.

08:19.082 --> 08:23.210
Yes, sir, Captain Davenport.
Yes, sir.

08:23.837 --> 08:26.213
We're rolling, captain.

09:09.257 --> 09:12.635
This is where they killed
Sergeant Waters last month, sir.

09:14.179 --> 09:16.764
Why did you say "they"
killed him, corporal?

09:19.017 --> 09:21.352
- Who's "they"?
- The Klan, sir.

09:21.561 --> 09:24.813
They ain't too crazy about us
tan yanks down here.

09:55.011 --> 09:57.596
I suppose whoever drove
you in from the station

09:57.806 --> 10:00.557
showed you the spot
where the killing took place.

10:00.934 --> 10:04.895
Told you I had all the troops'
personal effects searched for weapons.

10:07.649 --> 10:09.483
He tell you all that?

10:09.818 --> 10:12.778
Is there a point the colonel
is trying to make, sir?

10:13.196 --> 10:14.947
There's a point.

10:16.908 --> 10:20.327
This thing has been blown
all the hell out of shape.

10:20.787 --> 10:22.496
This is the Army's business.

10:22.914 --> 10:24.873
Not the NAACP.

10:25.375 --> 10:26.834
Not the Negro press.

10:27.168 --> 10:30.713
Not those paper-shuffling
desk jockeys in Washington.

10:31.589 --> 10:34.383
I was brought up
in the South, Davenport.

10:34.592 --> 10:36.802
Ever hear of
Threadgill County, Alabama?

10:37.012 --> 10:39.805
No, sir.

10:41.766 --> 10:43.475
No matter.

10:45.145 --> 10:49.273
I've been commanding colored
troops all my life, Davenport.

10:49.607 --> 10:52.818
The worst thing you can do
in this part of the country

10:53.028 --> 10:57.364
is pay attention to death of a Negro
under mysterious circumstances.

10:57.574 --> 10:59.158
Especially a soldier.

10:59.367 --> 11:02.244
People get itchy. Uneasy.

11:02.454 --> 11:06.123
White folk in the town,
colored at the fort.

11:06.708 --> 11:09.084
Keep turning this thing over,

11:09.294 --> 11:13.213
sooner or later, you're bound
to have an explosion.

11:13.548 --> 11:19.303
Now, I've lived here
in Hunter Parish three years.

11:19.679 --> 11:21.930
I'm fond of the place.

11:22.140 --> 11:23.724
I like the duty.

11:23.933 --> 11:25.351
You get my meaning?

11:25.560 --> 11:27.311
What is it you want, colonel?

11:27.520 --> 11:30.814
I want whatever you came here
to do completed in three days.

11:31.024 --> 11:33.525
Sir, I request permission
to notify Washington.

11:33.735 --> 11:35.652
Denied.
I'm under direct orders...

11:35.904 --> 11:38.238
I don't give a damn
if Roosevelt sent you.

11:38.448 --> 11:42.993
I'm trying to prevent my troops from
going into town and killing somebody.

11:43.203 --> 11:45.704
And I don't care what you think.

11:46.122 --> 11:48.040
You can always return
to Washington.

11:48.208 --> 11:49.249
No, sir.

11:49.417 --> 11:53.545
I was assigned this case
and I intend to file a report, sir.

11:58.176 --> 12:00.386
Here are your instructions
and our reports.

12:00.553 --> 12:02.596
Taylor's men
will help you get settled.

12:02.764 --> 12:04.932
Taylor was Waters' CO.

12:05.141 --> 12:06.725
That'll be all, Davenport.

12:14.067 --> 12:17.069
Oh, and, captain?

12:17.737 --> 12:19.321
Remember,

12:19.489 --> 12:22.866
you're the first colored officer
most of these men have seen.

12:23.535 --> 12:27.162
The Army expects you to set
an example for the colored troops

12:27.372 --> 12:29.748
and be a credit to your race.

12:30.333 --> 12:33.794
Is that clear, captain?

12:35.088 --> 12:37.965
Yes, colonel.

12:43.054 --> 12:44.596
Sir.

12:45.765 --> 12:47.516
Sir, you all right?

12:47.725 --> 12:51.019
You like to go to your quarters?
No, I'll see Captain Taylor.

12:51.229 --> 12:54.440
You don't wanna unpack, sir?
Freshen up? Didn't go too good?

12:54.607 --> 12:58.444
You got a hearing problem?
No, sir. I was born with big ears.

12:58.653 --> 13:01.572
It runs in my family.
My grandmother had big ears...

13:21.593 --> 13:24.178
I used to drive
a fire truck, captain.

13:24.387 --> 13:27.598
Then the Army took and let
me drive an ambulance.

13:27.807 --> 13:30.893
I've been driving this jeep
for six months, sir.

13:31.102 --> 13:33.520
Only turned over twice.

13:34.272 --> 13:36.523
- Twice?
- Yes, sir.

13:37.484 --> 13:39.067
Good.

14:08.306 --> 14:10.516
- Good afternoon, sir.
- Good afternoon, sir.

14:18.566 --> 14:21.485
Sergeant Washington, sir.
Can I help you, captain?

14:21.694 --> 14:23.904
Captain Davenport
to see Captain Taylor.

14:25.031 --> 14:27.241
Just a moment, sir.

14:29.369 --> 14:30.953
Yes?

14:31.162 --> 14:34.164
There's a Captain Davenport
to see you, sir.

14:34.374 --> 14:37.251
- Well, send him in.
- Yes, sir.

14:38.670 --> 14:41.713
Every member of the lodge
is rooting for you, sir.

14:50.348 --> 14:53.642
- Have a seat.
- Thank you.

14:53.851 --> 14:56.270
I like your flowers, captain.

15:00.066 --> 15:01.400
Hey, where's he from?

15:01.609 --> 15:03.443
He's from Washington, D.C.

15:03.611 --> 15:05.612
He's here on special assignment.

15:05.822 --> 15:07.072
Washington?

15:07.282 --> 15:08.740
Yes, sir.

15:08.950 --> 15:11.451
You gotta be shitting me.

15:13.121 --> 15:17.499
So they assigned a lawyer
to the military police, eh?

15:17.709 --> 15:20.210
Well, where did you graduate
law school?

15:20.420 --> 15:22.379
Howard University.

15:22.672 --> 15:24.381
Your parents rich or something?

15:24.716 --> 15:26.883
No, my father's a mailman.

15:29.262 --> 15:31.513
I graduated at the Point.

15:31.931 --> 15:34.266
I didn't see any Negroes
at the Point.

15:34.475 --> 15:39.605
In fact, I never saw a Negro
until I was, I think, 12 or 13.

15:39.814 --> 15:41.648
Have you seen
my orders, captain?

15:42.442 --> 15:45.360
Yes, as soon as Colonel
Nivens received them.

15:45.695 --> 15:51.742
Look, I think it only fair to tell you
that had I known you'd be a Negro

15:51.951 --> 15:55.912
I would've requested the immediate
suspension of the investigation.

15:56.122 --> 15:59.583
Now, look, may I speak freely?
You haven't stopped yet.

16:00.418 --> 16:03.962
Look, these local people aren't
gonna charge a white man

16:04.172 --> 16:05.922
in this parish on your say-so.

16:06.132 --> 16:07.633
And Nivens knows that.

16:07.842 --> 16:11.470
He doesn't give a damn about this killing.
Your being here proves it.

16:11.679 --> 16:15.807
Making a fool out of you. Can't you...?
Will you take off those sunglasses?

16:16.017 --> 16:18.935
I like these.
They're like MacArthur's.

16:19.437 --> 16:22.856
All right. Now, look. Let me
explain something to you.

16:23.066 --> 16:24.941
You go near Tynin in uniform,

16:25.109 --> 16:27.736
sounding white
and charging local people,

16:27.904 --> 16:30.364
you're gonna wind up
just as dead as Waters.

16:30.573 --> 16:33.825
This isn't Washington, Davenport.
I know where I am.

16:34.035 --> 16:37.746
Do you know how many times I've asked
Nivens to look into this killing?

16:37.955 --> 16:40.082
Every day since it happened.

16:40.291 --> 16:43.585
Do you suspect someone?
Don't play lawyer with me, soldier.

16:43.795 --> 16:46.880
With you on this case,
we are not gonna get anywhere.

16:47.090 --> 16:49.675
Like it or not, captain.
I am all you've got.

16:49.884 --> 16:52.511
Your orders instruct you
to cooperate.

16:54.389 --> 16:58.350
Now, is there anything else?

16:59.811 --> 17:02.396
- Ellis.
- Yes, sir.

17:02.605 --> 17:05.607
Captain Davenport will need
some assistance with the men.

17:05.817 --> 17:08.402
You'll excuse me, captain?
Oh, I'm glad I met you.

17:10.655 --> 17:12.571
Captain.

17:24.001 --> 17:26.420
I sure hope we get
to fight soon, sir.

17:26.628 --> 17:29.339
Next, they'll have us picking
this year's cotton crop.

17:29.507 --> 17:32.634
Don't worry, they don't grow
a lot of cotton in Germany.

17:32.844 --> 17:34.636
Yes, sir.

17:37.932 --> 17:40.600
How long was Captain Taylor's
investigation?

17:40.977 --> 17:42.018
Two days, sir.

17:42.770 --> 17:44.771
Two days? Who did he question?

17:45.148 --> 17:48.024
Well, mostly guys who had
contact with sarge that day.

17:48.234 --> 17:51.820
Guys in his platoon, then anybody
who could've seen him on the road.

17:52.029 --> 17:53.447
Wasn't but a handful.

17:53.656 --> 17:56.324
- Did you see him that day?
- Nope.

17:56.784 --> 17:58.493
No, sir.

18:24.270 --> 18:27.981
Did your sergeant drink a lot?
I didn't know him well enough, sir.

18:28.191 --> 18:31.234
All right, soldiers, let's
get back to those exercises.

18:31.444 --> 18:33.904
Haven't you ever seen
a colored officer before?

18:34.113 --> 18:36.531
No, sir. Have you, sir?

18:38.242 --> 18:39.659
Ten-hut.

18:46.667 --> 18:47.709
This is it, sir.

18:47.919 --> 18:51.671
The captain instructed everyone in
the sergeant's platoon to be here.

18:53.716 --> 18:55.509
As you were.

19:06.354 --> 19:09.064
Sergeant Waters' room
is right there, sir.

19:09.565 --> 19:13.568
Sir, I think I ought to tell you, sir.

19:13.778 --> 19:18.198
Captain Taylor questioned two white
officers from this fort that night.

19:18.699 --> 19:19.866
How do you know?

19:20.076 --> 19:22.452
I delivered his report
to Colonel Nivens, sir.

19:22.662 --> 19:26.122
And on the way over,
the jeep hit a hole, bam!

19:26.541 --> 19:28.667
And the papers
flew all over the road

19:28.876 --> 19:31.711
and I happened to notice it, sir.
Who are they?

19:31.921 --> 19:33.004
No names, sir.

19:33.214 --> 19:35.298
Just the mentioning
of the questioning.

19:35.466 --> 19:37.551
Seems they were
on the road that night.

19:44.851 --> 19:50.021
Well, don't let any more reports
fly away from you, corporal.

19:50.606 --> 19:51.982
No, sir.

19:54.151 --> 19:56.319
Sir, may I say something,
though?

19:56.696 --> 20:01.241
It sure is good seeing one of
us wearing captain's bars, sir.

20:02.201 --> 20:04.202
Call in the first man, corporal.

20:04.662 --> 20:06.288
Yes, sir.

20:06.789 --> 20:09.249
Private Wilkie,
captain wants to see you.

20:09.458 --> 20:12.878
Yes, indeedy. On my way.

20:15.840 --> 20:18.550
Private Wilkie
reports as ordered, sir.

20:19.427 --> 20:21.052
Close the door.

20:29.020 --> 20:32.230
- Have a seat.
- Yes, sir.

20:36.068 --> 20:39.195
I'm Captain Davenport. I'm conduc...
We all know that, sir.

20:39.405 --> 20:43.575
Word went out on the grapevine you
were here the minute you hit the fort.

20:48.372 --> 20:52.792
I'm conducting an inquiry into the
events surrounding the death of Waters.

20:52.960 --> 20:55.754
The report I file
will be confidential.

20:57.048 --> 20:58.798
How long did you know
the sergeant?

20:59.550 --> 21:01.301
About a year, sir.

21:01.510 --> 21:04.846
You see, this company, sir,
was basically a baseball team.

21:05.056 --> 21:07.766
Most of the guys had played
in the Negro league.

21:07.975 --> 21:10.143
Naturally,
the Army put us all together.

21:10.353 --> 21:14.105
The Army sent Sergeant Waters here
to manage the team, summer of '42,

21:14.315 --> 21:16.650
right after the invasion
of North Africa.

21:16.859 --> 21:20.070
He'd been in field artillery,
a gunnery sergeant.

21:20.279 --> 21:22.948
He had a FEF and an ETO.

21:23.157 --> 21:26.409
A Croix de Guerre
from the First World War.

21:27.703 --> 21:29.579
What kind of man was he?

21:34.502 --> 21:37.837
He was all spit and polish, sir.

21:38.631 --> 21:41.716
He took my stripes, sir,
but I was in the wrong.

21:41.926 --> 21:43.510
Sergeant Wilkie.

21:43.719 --> 21:47.180
You're a noncommissioned officer
in the army of a country at war.

21:47.390 --> 21:50.308
Penalty for being drunk on duty
is severe in peace time.

21:50.518 --> 21:55.105
So don't bring me, "Us colored folks
can't do nothing unless they're drunk."

21:55.314 --> 21:57.273
You're supposed to be
an example.

21:57.692 --> 22:01.486
I'm gonna put you in the stockade
for 10 days and take those stripes.

22:01.696 --> 22:03.822
Wait, sergeant...
To teach you a lesson.

22:04.031 --> 22:05.615
You're in the Army.

22:07.702 --> 22:09.869
Colored folks running off
at the mouth.

22:10.037 --> 22:13.873
What will they do if the white man
give them a chance? What do you do?

22:14.083 --> 22:17.836
You wind up drunk on guard duty.
I don't blame the white man.

22:18.045 --> 22:20.880
Why the hell should he put
colored and white together?

22:21.090 --> 22:23.925
You can't guard your own quarters.
Sergeant...

22:24.135 --> 22:28.179
Where's your pride, soldier? Where's
your respect for this uniform?

22:28.431 --> 22:31.850
Get out of my sight, private.

22:52.079 --> 22:54.247
And how was he
with the other men?

22:54.457 --> 22:56.833
Sometimes the Southern
guys caught hell.

22:57.043 --> 23:00.378
Sergeant wasn't too big
on guys from the South.

23:01.130 --> 23:03.840
Me, I'm from Detroit.

23:04.091 --> 23:07.052
Did you know that Joe Louis
got his start in Detroit?

23:07.470 --> 23:09.304
What about the Southern men?

23:09.513 --> 23:11.931
The sarge didn't like them.
Except for C.J.

23:12.141 --> 23:15.643
It could've been because C.J. was
the best ballplayer on the team.

23:15.853 --> 23:17.812
He could sing too.

23:18.022 --> 23:20.190
Boy, could he sing.

23:24.070 --> 23:25.862
♪ Well, it's a lowdown ♪

23:27.573 --> 23:29.449
♪ Lowdown dirty shame ♪

23:31.577 --> 23:33.244
♪ Yes, it's a lowdown ♪

23:35.039 --> 23:37.082
♪ Lowdown dirty shame ♪

23:39.960 --> 23:43.797
♪ They say we're fighting Hitler
But they won't let us in the game ♪

23:44.131 --> 23:45.799
♪ Lord ♪

23:46.258 --> 23:50.929
♪ Yes, it's a lowdown dirty shame ♪

23:53.724 --> 23:58.645
♪ Yes, it's a lowdown
Dirty, stinking shame ♪

23:58.813 --> 24:02.023
Oh, sing it for Big Mary,
you little sweet thing.

24:02.191 --> 24:03.650
♪ Left home to join this Army ♪

24:03.818 --> 24:05.860
♪ Won't somebody tell me
Who's to blame? ♪

24:06.028 --> 24:08.488
I'll tell you something,
C.J., right now.

24:08.739 --> 24:11.282
